06434nam a22009975i 9781771120364DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97817711203647 a10.51644/97817711203642doi  a(DE-B1597)667197  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aD810 W7bW67 2015 INTERNET 7aBIO0220002bisacsh04a940.5308222300aWorking Memory :bWomen and Work in World War II /ced. by Jeanne Perreault, Marlene Kadar. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (251 p.) :b52 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLife Writing00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tThe Lives and the Archives -- t“Things Gone Astray” -- t“People Dealt This Fate To People” -- tRe-Dressing Women’s History in the Special Operations Executive -- tTwo Sisters -- tFrom Planter’s Daughter To Imperial Soldier And Servant In Britain’s War -- tResisting Holocaust Memory -- t“Snow White In Auschwitz” -- tPerpetual Pioneers -- t“Girl Takes Drastic Step” -- t“These Dutch Girls Are Wizard!” -- tFacing Death -- tAcknowledgements -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tBooks in the Life Writing Series Published by Wilfrid Laurier University Press0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWorking Memory: Women and Work in World War II speaks to the work women did during the war: the labour of survival, resistance, and collaboration, and the labour of recording, representing, and memorializing these wartime experiences. The contributors follow their subjects’ tracks and deepen our understanding of the experiences from the imprints left behind. These efforts are a part of the making of history, and when the process is as personal as many of our contributors’ research has been, it is also the working of memory. The implication here is that memory is intimate, and that the layering of narrative fragments that recovery involves brings us in touching distance to ourselves. These are not the stories of the brave little woman at home; they are stories of the woman who calculated the main chance and took up with the Nazi soldier, or who eagerly dropped the apron at the door and picked up a paintbrush, or who brazenly bargained for her life and her mother’s with the most feared of tyrants. These are stories of courage and sometimes of compromise— not the courage of bravado and hype and big guns, but rather the courage of hard choices and sacrifices that make sense of the life given, even when that life seems only madness. Working Memory brings scholarly attention to the roles of women in World War II that have been hidden, masked, undervalued, or forgotten.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xWar workxWomen. 4aArchival Studies. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aHistory: Military History. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh  aAuschwitz- Birkenau.  aBarbados.  aBritish Army.  aCanadian military.  aNatzweiler.  aRavensbruck.  aRoyal Australian Air Force.  aWarsaw Ghetto.  aarchives.  aconcentration camp.  acultural and communicative memory.  aethics and testimony.  aexile.  afemale agents.  agender.  aholocaust.  alife writing.  awar artist.  awar crimes.  awomen in the military.  awomen photojournalists.1 aBrannan, Beverly W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrinson, Charmian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerris, Lesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKadar, Marlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKadar, Marlene, 